Escape the Batcave

by: Ashay Moorjani

This game was made for my level 2 project at The League of Amazing Programmers.
Click here to download and play!

1. Why I Made This Game

I decided to make an escape room game because they are fun to create and to play. I've always liked different types of strategy games and I thought the Batcave theming would give it a unique touch.

2. What I Learned

I learned from user testing that a few of the puzzles were a bit too challenging to overcome. The players that tested my game got stuck on a couple of the obstacles, which might have made it seem boring at times.

3. Architecture of My Game

My game is set up in a format where there are multiple screens (rooms) that can be accessed using the arrow keys. I have mouse listeners which allow many objects to be clicked with the mouse to give clues to the player. Some of my classes that contain pictures/objects know when something else has been clicked, allowing the player to progress in the game.

4. Technical Implementation

While I was working on my game, I realized that just the three main game screens would get boring after a while. I had played an escape room game earlier for inspiration and remembered that it had new rooms that could be unlocked when the player had completed a certain task. I was able to add a fourth room that could only open once the player had found a specific item. I accomplished this using if statements and variables that both my GamePanel and my objects could understand. The new clues that the fourth room adds to the experience makes the game much more enjoyable.

5. Most Challenging Part

In my opinion, the most challenging part of this project was the escape room aspect of it. I had to come up with varying puzzles that would have the right level of difficulty and would not be boring. I also wanted to have a clear story going on and multiple options for the player, so the clues could be found in different orders. In the final game, I have locked compartments that need codes to open, people that give the player a new clue in return for an item, and random objects hidden around the Batcave. There are also multiple clues available right from the start to offer more possibilities to the player.

6. Future Fixes and Updates

One component that many other escape room games have is a bar to keep track of the items that the player currently has. I purposely chose not to include this because I didn't exactly know how to pull it off. However, I think it would be a useful addition to consider in the future, as it makes the game simpler for the player. An improvement suggested by my test players was to change up a couple of obstacles. I think the way to approach this would be to increase the amount of steps taken to beat the game, but make them easier to complete.
